      "message": "So I looked into this. This duration isn\u0027t very helpful right now, because it\u0027s actually the duration elapsed since the *last* callback.\n\nIn addition, the first callback always reports with the wrong duration, since time.Time is initialized to the Unix epoch (thanks martiniss for finding this out)\n```\n--git a/client/downloader/downloader.go b/client/downloader/downloader.go\nindex 44c0e720b..478a639d8 100644\n--- a/client/downloader/downloader.go\n+++ b/client/downloader/downloader.go\n@@ -303,9 +303,11 @@ func (d *Downloader) updateFileStats(lockedCb func(*FileStats) bool) {\n                if d.options.FileStatsCallback !\u003d nil {\n                        doCall \u003d maybeCall\n                        now :\u003d clock.Now(d.ctx)\n-                       span \u003d now.Sub(d.lastFileStatsCb)\n+                       if !d.lastFileStatsCb.IsZero() {\n+                               span \u003d now.Sub(d.lastFileStatsCb)\n+                       }\n \n-                       if span \u003e\u003d d.interval {\n+                       if d.lastFileStatsCb.IsZero() || span \u003e\u003d d.interval {\n                                if d.interval \u003c d.options.MaxFileStatsInterval {\n                                        d.interval *\u003d 2\n                                        if d.interval \u003e d.options.MaxFileStatsInterval {\n```\n\nBut even like this, the duration isn\u0027t super helpful. Maybe we should change it to elapsed... but I\u0027ll look into making that (or documenting time.Duration in the callback) change in a followup.",
